<h3><strong>Ok! The price is right!</strong></h3>

<p class="block-img"><img src="https://prismic-io.s3.amazonaws.com/solede/cf42078998adb982a9f85236b4a9c3777dff1b57_conto-barista.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="513" /></p>

<p>If your destination for your holiday in Italy is a touristic city or area, you should keep a watchful eye on prices. Restaurants and cafés might be much more expensive than they should be in very central and touristic areas: in many of these places you are not actually paying for sublime product quality or service, but mostly for the exclusive location. If you want to be an aware consumer, here is our list of average prices for some daily expenses you might have during your holiday to Italy: </p>

<p>- Pizza at restaurant or pizzeria is around 6/7 Euros.</p>

<p>- A pasta dish, let&#39;s say penne with tomato sauce, should cost no more than 10 Euros. If more, we can consider the restaurant quite expensive </p>

<p>- Espresso coffee standing up at the counter can vary between 0,70 cents and 1 euro. If you sit at the table you will pay for service and &quot;coperto&quot; (the cover charge)</p>

<p>- At a café, a small bottle of water costs around 1 Euro. Natural spring water costs as much as sparkling water. If you find a supermarket, we suggest you to buy water there.</p>

<p>- Entering in a Gelateria, a small cup of gelato may cost from 1,50 to 2,60 Euros.</p>

