<h3><strong>Watch out for pickpockets!</strong></h3>

<p class="block-img"><img src="https://prismic-io.s3.amazonaws.com/solede/0cf70f5617c142c794c958d7046171a8146fda27_pickpockets.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="514" /></p>

<p>In some parts of Italy, particularly in big cities, purse-snatching and pickpocketing can be quite an issue. Crowded places like stations, airports, buses and tourist areas are the best hunting grounds for pickpockets, who can act undisturbed while inattentive tourists are looking at their map, waiting right in the middle of a queue, or looking for the right stop of their bus.<br>We are not saying that you should watch your back for the entire trip, but few tips may help you not to have your holiday to Italy completely ruined by these unpleasant petty thefts.</p>

<p>Firts of all, be discreet. Avoid putting your wallet in the back pocket of your jeans where it can be easily seen (and taken) by any malicious person; for the same reason, your backpack front pocket is not the good hiding place to secure your cash and plastics either. We suggest you to put your wallet, passport, cash and plastics in a fanny pack, or at the bottom of your backpack. Make sure that the zip of your bag or backpack is always perfectly closed and check it several times during the day. Keep a close eye on your belongings!</p>

<p>Our second suggestion is that there is no need to carry your passport, car licence or prescriptions everywhere you go: make photocopies of important documents and store them in a separate part of your luggage. During your daily tours, take with you only things you are going to need: you may consider leaving at hotel your laptop, passport or additional cash you may not need. In Italy we like to say “prevenire è meglio che curare”, which means “an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure”.</p>

