<h3><strong>Using ATMs in Italy</strong></h3>

<p class="block-img"><img src="https://prismic-io.s3.amazonaws.com/solede/f92bc314c3a99c9f9a99067c56686e2605c3ddd6_dx_bancomat.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="515" /></p>

<p>Before leaving to Italy, pay your bank a visit and inform them of your trip and destination, so they won’t put a block on your cards when oversea. Ask the bank what is the transaction fee you are going to pay for each time you use an ATM, and if there is a currency conversion charged every time you withdraw money. If you are charged for every transaction, then withdraw larger amounts every time you make a visit to the ATM, so you’ll go fewer times! </p>

<p>Throughout Italy you will find ATMs to get your cash. In big cities you will find ATMs at every corner, especially in central areas. On the contrary, if you are visiting small villages off the beaten path, you may find only one ATM in the entire village. ATMs are called Bancomat in Italy and they are really easy to use, since you can choose the language preferred as soon as you insert your card. You’ll be asked to insert your PIN by digits, so make sure to know it and type it correctly! The ATM will withdraw money directly from your bank account at home, convert it into Euro and give you cash. It&#39;s as easy as that!</p>

