<h3><strong>To tip or not to tip, that is the question</strong></h3>

<p class="block-img"><img src="https://prismic-io.s3.amazonaws.com/solede/6598be0b9a2fb89d31b5fc04fac8301a4395b8e1_mancia.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="475" /></p>

<p>You may have read or heard several things about tips in Italy, and you might feel a bit confused or not know what to really do when facing a waiter. We’d like to face the issue from the Italian point of view, so our suggestion is to relax, this is not a really big issue for us, so feel free to do what you want to do. First of all, tips are not compulsory at all in Italy, nor common. Waiters in regular restaurants would never expect a tip from their Italian customers, and this is simply because Italians don’t tip that much, even when they have particularly appreciated the food and service: they would pay many compliments on the cooking, leave a positive review on Tripadvisor, but few of them would leave a tip. This does not mean that Italians never tip at all but even when travelling abroad, waiters do not expect generous tips from Italians.<br></p>

<p>Reading your bill at the restaurant you might be puzzled finding 1 or 2 euros per person to be paid under the entry “il coperto”. This is the cover charge and if you read it on your bill, do not think you have been ripped off by the restaurant, since this is the price for occupying their territory for a bit.</p>

