<h3><strong>Cash is Italy’s best friend</strong></h3>

<p class="block-img"><img src="https://prismic-io.s3.amazonaws.com/solede/2e04ea4416272f5d971de5a5ce7b521d11cb70e0_cash.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="514" /></p>

<p>Although debit and credit cards have gain acceptance in Italy and almost everyone under the age of 60 has a plastic or two, it is still weird for Italians to pay by card for a coffee at a bar or for bread at the grocery, and this can even have a jarring effect on the seller, who would ask you if you really do not have some coins to pay for that. This may not occur in big cities like Rome, Milan, Venice or Florence, but as long as you travel away from the bustle, you may find restaurants, grocery stores and shops which balk when you try to hand them a Visa. <br>For those of you who are accustomed to paying for their coffee at Starbucks with a debit card, we strongly suggest to always keep some cash with you during your holiday in Italy. </p>

